Dialogue: 0,0:00:02.89,0:00:05.28,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,{\fad(800,0)}On January 8th, in 1986,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.28,0:00:09.45,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,a short essay titled "The Conscience of a Hacker" was shared online.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.45,0:00:13.00,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,It was written shortly after the arrest of a hacker known as The Mentor,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:13.00,0:00:15.81,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,an attempt to define the hacker ethos.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:16.29,0:00:18.35,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,The end of the essay states the following:
Dialogue: 0,0:00:19.16,0:00:21.16,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"We seek after knowledge,"
Dialogue: 0,0:00:21.16,0:00:22.80,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"and you call us criminals."
Dialogue: 0,0:00:23.20,0:00:25.74,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"We exist without skin color, without nationality,"
Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.75,0:00:27.62,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"without religious bias,"
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.62,0:00:29.78,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"and you call us criminals."
Dialogue: 0,0:00:29.78,0:00:31.48,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"Yes, I am a criminal,"
Dialogue: 0,0:00:32.11,0:00:34.41,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"my crime is that of curiosity."
Dialogue: 0,0:00:34.94,0:00:38.43,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"You may stop me, but you can't stop us all."
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.21,0:00:41.20,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"That's cool."
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.20,0:00:43.67,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,All right, there are three different kinds:
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.67,0:00:45.27,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,there's white hat - the good guys,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.27,0:00:47.23,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,there's gray hat - the good and bad guys,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.23,0:00:48.27,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,and then there's black hat -
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.81,0:00:50.82,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,just the bad guys.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.82,0:00:53.63,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,They're comprised of coders, engineers, social engineers,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:53.63,0:00:57.33,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,activists, network specialists, scammers,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.33,0:00:58.95,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,crackers, and exploiters.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.95,0:01:01.21,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Some of them work alone, some of them work in groups.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.21,0:01:03.04,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,And some of them even work for the government,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:04.21,0:01:05.75,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,I mean until they don't.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.75,0:01:06.79,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,They're the outcasts,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.79,0:01:08.04,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,the antisocial nerds,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.04,0:01:10.30,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,the losers with computers.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.31,0:01:12.95,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,But, they're also the ones who got rich off Bitcoin,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.95,0:01:15.67,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,the ones who throw a crazy party in Las Vegas every year,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:15.67,0:01:18.30,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,the ones who start billion-dollar tech companies,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.30,0:01:21.04,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,the ones who steal millions of dollars from those tech companies.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:21.38,0:01:23.94,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,They're the ones who have changed the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.94,0:01:26.10,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,They are the hackers.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:27.44,0:01:29.24,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,But how did we even get here?
Dialogue: 0,0:01:34.24,0:01:37.46,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Our story begins right at the start of what many now call
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.46,0:01:38.46,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,the culture decade.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.63,0:01:46.19,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,In the early 1960s,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:46.19,0:01:48.29,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,a rebellious and transformative culture
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.29,0:01:52.38,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,took root within the prestigious halls of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.59,0:01:55.99,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,The beginning of hacker culture started on campus in Building 20,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.99,0:01:59.72,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,a structure which has since been deemed "The Magical Incubator".
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.72,0:02:01.13,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Located on the third floor,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:01.13,0:02:05.33,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,you could find a crowded classroom that space was absolutely dominated
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.33,0:02:08.19,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,by a carefully constructed layout of model train tracks.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.56,0:02:13.60,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,This space was the home to MIT's very own Tech Model Railroad Club.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.60,0:02:16.20,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,The club consisted of different groups that worked together
Dialogue: 0,0:02:16.20,0:02:20.49,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,towards their common goal of automating the operation of model trains.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.49,0:02:23.37,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Some focused on crafting historical train replicas,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.37,0:02:25.05,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,others on scenery and buildings,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.05,0:02:27.01,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,but it was one group in particular,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.01,0:02:29.26,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,the signals and power subcommittee,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:29.26,0:02:32.32,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,who were responsible for first popularizing the term:
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.33,0:02:33.25,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"hacker."
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.26,0:02:37.27,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,this group was mainly responsible for creating the circuits that operated the trains
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.27,0:02:40.35,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,they were basically the engineers behind the whole operation.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.35,0:02:44.01,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,One member of the subcommittee was a guy named Peter Samson
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.01,0:02:49.60,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Now it's important to understand that Peter was absolutely obsessed with electronics and automation,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:49.60,0:02:52.81,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,and he was always looking for new ways to be creative
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.81,0:02:56.89,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,and pioneer new systems, to operate model trains within the TMRC.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.60,0:03:01.20,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,He was also someone who loved to explore.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.15,0:03:06.70,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,One {\i1}fateful night{\i0} around 2:00 in the morning,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.70,0:03:09.96,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,he roamed the basement hallways of Building 26
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.96,0:03:11.55,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,in search of something intriguing.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.55,0:03:15.87,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Little did he know that this nocturnal exploration would lead him to a discovery,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.87,0:03:18.67,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,propelling him into a new realm of creativity
Dialogue: 0,0:03:18.67,0:03:21.01,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,and even the beginning of a new lifestyle.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.50,0:03:26.25,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Upon entering an area that was labeled the Electronic Accounting Machinery Room,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.25,0:03:29.85,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Peter caught his first glimpse of an IBM 704,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:29.85,0:03:34.22,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,a multi-million dollar mainframe that took up almost the entirety of the space.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.74,0:03:38.33,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Now, Peter was definitely not supposed to be here,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.33,0:03:41.11,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,as the room was usually heavily staffed during the day,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.11,0:03:46.67,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,and only people with official security clearance from MIT, were allowed to operate the computer in the first place.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.56,0:03:48.56,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,But...
Dialogue: 0,0:03:48.56,0:03:50.32,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,no one was ever there at 2 a.m.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.72,0:03:53.07,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Alongside other members of the TMRC,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.07,0:03:56.75,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Peter would regularly sneak into the basement of Building 26 at night
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.75,0:04:00.19,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,to use the computer and other devices held by the EAM room.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.63,0:04:05.89,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,These acts of defiance would mark the beginning of hacker culture as we now know it today.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.89,0:04:09.13,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Machine time was extremely, tight.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.13,0:04:09.93,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Uh...
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.93,0:04:11.84,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,They found times in the middle of the night,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.84,0:04:14.27,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,maybe in unlocked computer rooms where they could do these things.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.27,0:04:15.78,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,The liberal arts majors, {\s1\b0}who{\s0\b1}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.78,0:04:18.04,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,whose only computer time available was if they
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.04,0:04:20.91,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,gummed up the locks and sneak into the building late at night
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.91,0:04:22.78,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,because they weren't allowed to sign up for this stuff
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.78,0:04:28.98,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,The people that took a systematic approach toward the development of {\s1}uh{\s0} computer software
Dialogue: 0,0:04:28.98,0:04:30.07,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,missed the boat.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.07,0:04:33.86,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,It was a trial and error (for) people working illegally, in the underground
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.86,0:04:35.44,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,This move made most (of) the advances.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.33,0:04:41.44,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,In the following years, the TMRC would continue tinkering with computer technology
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.44,0:04:43.68,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,whether they had permission or not.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:44.22,0:04:45.59,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,But to be honest,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.59,0:04:48.51,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,using model trains as your excuse to be a hacker,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.51,0:04:50.93,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,could really only get you so far.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.93,0:04:56.25,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Subsequently, many TMRC members that were a part of the Signals and Power Subcommittee
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.25,0:04:59.75,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,went on to join MIT's Artificial Intelligence Lab.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.75,0:05:03.08,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Led by the MIT Lab Director Marvin Minsky,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.08,0:05:05.49,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,these early hackers had found a supportive mentor.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.08,0:05:11.93,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Impressed by their determination, Minsky allowed them direct access to the machines.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.29,0:05:15.36,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,And with that, the lab members went to work.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:15.36,0:05:18.22,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Among the many achievements of the MIT AI Lab
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.23,0:05:20.30,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,was the creation of {\i1}Spacewar!{\i0},
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.30,0:05:24.58,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,one of the first video games predating {\i1}Pong{\i0} by a decade.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:24.58,0:05:28.96,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"So those stars is a part from Peter Samson wrote called {\\i1}Expensive Planetarium{\\i0}."
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.96,0:05:32.77,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"And it's ..." (Laugh)
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.77,0:05:35.02,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,With the success of visionaries at MIT,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.02,0:05:37.31,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,and as the 1960s unfolded,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.31,0:05:40.59,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,the hacker ethos began to spread like wildfire,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.59,0:05:44.78,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,igniting centers of innovation at universities across the nation.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.78,0:05:49.41,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,From Carnegie Mellon to Stanford, the spirit of exploration thrived,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.41,0:05:52.75,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,fostering a new breed of technological pioneers.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.22,0:05:57.87,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,At this point, hacker culture seemed to be quite contained to the more academic circles,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:57.87,0:06:00.77,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,and it actually seemed like it was going to stay that way for a while.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:00.77,0:06:06.82,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,But it wasn't long until hacking spawned the comp-sci student dropout cliché, that we know all too well today.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.37,0:06:08.49,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,It all starts
Dialogue: 0,0:06:08.49,0:06:09.50,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,with the telephone.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.14,0:06:16.13,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"You know, Steve was never like you or me,"
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.13,0:06:18.32,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"he always saw things differently."
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.32,0:06:22.13,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"Steve and I found this weird guy who was a hero around Berkeley,"
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.45,0:06:24.82,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"all because he found a way to beat the system."
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.82,0:06:26.75,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"This guy was called Captain Crunch"
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.75,0:06:28.02,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"because he figured out,"
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.64,0:06:33.44,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"this little whistle that you found in boxes of Cap'n Crunch cereal"
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.44,0:06:36.61,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"had the same tones as AT&T's long-distance equipment."
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.12,0:06:42.79,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"So you got free phone calls anywhere in the world, {\s1}with{\s0} with this thing I built called the blue box."
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.79,0:06:45.00,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"And then we tested it out by calling the Pope."
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.00,0:06:45.90,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"You talk."
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.90,0:06:48.30,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"No, no, they're not putting you through to the Pope, are they?"
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.30,0:06:51.99,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,There was a huge culture shift when John Draper, also known as Captain Crunch,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.99,0:06:54.51,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,helped pioneer the world of phone phreaking
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.51,0:06:55.85,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,By blowing into that toy whistle.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.04,0:06:57.24,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,{\i1}*beep{\i0}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.24,0:06:59.81,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Draper and countless others fooled the phone company,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.81,0:07:02.27,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,and made free calls all around the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.27,0:07:06.53,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,When the two Steves began developing and distributing the aforementioned blue boxes,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:06.53,0:07:10.95,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,it actually marked one of the first times hacker culture garnered attention from the mainstream media.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.95,0:07:14.67,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,When Esquire magazine wrote about it in a 1971 article,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.67,0:07:15.92,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,released in the same year.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.92,0:07:19.95,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Freaking was also covered prominently in Abby Hoffman's now infamous publication,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.95,0:07:21.01,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"Steal This Book."
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.01,0:07:24.13,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Now to be clear, freaking wasn't just about making free calls,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.13,0:07:26.30,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,not to the hackers back then at least.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.30,0:07:29.05,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Freaking was a new way to learn how the phone network worked,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.05,0:07:30.78,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,a way to pull some harmless pranks,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.78,0:07:33.76,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,a way to build a community within a growing subculture,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.76,0:07:35.02,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,and in some cases,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.44,0:07:38.14,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,a way to just simply stick it to the man.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.97,0:07:41.95,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Honestly, it can be argued that freaking turned out to be
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.95,0:07:46.98,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,one of, if not the most influential aspects of hacker culture we've seen to date.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.98,0:07:49.40,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,With Steve Jobs even going as far as to say that,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.40,0:07:51.59,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"if it had not been for Wozniak's blue boxes,"
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.59,0:07:52.84,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"there wouldn't have been an Apple."
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.32,0:07:55.74,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,This isn't the last time freaking will come up in this video,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.74,0:07:58.36,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,as it definitely continued to evolve over the years.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.68,0:07:59.47,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,But for now,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.84,0:08:02.08,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,let's go back to the topic of computers.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.34,0:08:07.50,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"What's the mail this morning?"
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.66,0:08:10.16,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"This one looks interesting, let's uh take a look at this."
Dialogue: 0,0:08:10.16,0:08:11.88,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"I'm going to need a couple of copies of this."
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.88,0:08:15.33,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"You'll have a television screen like this here, and a keyboard."
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.33,0:08:17.16,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"And you'll talk to the computer, get information from it,"
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.16,0:08:19.35,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"and you'll take it as much for granted as we take the telephone."
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.35,0:08:22.47,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"I wonder that what sort of a life would it be like in social terms?"
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.28,0:08:25.02,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"Their whole life is built around the computer."
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.02,0:08:27.03,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"Do we become a computer-dependent society?"
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.03,0:08:29.86,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"In some ways, but they {\s1}eh{\s0} would also enrich our society,"
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.86,0:08:31.17,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"and this is a wonderful thing."
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.17,0:08:33.02,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,As the 1970s progressed,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.02,0:08:36.07,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,so did the interconnectedness of computer networks.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.07,0:08:40.38,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,The rise of ARPANET provided a new frontier for exploration and experimentation.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.84,0:08:43.27,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,I'll try not to bore you, but for those unfamiliar,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:43.27,0:08:47.46,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,ARPANET was a computer network that helped lay the groundwork for the modern Internet.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.46,0:08:49.22,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,It started out in the late '60s,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.22,0:08:53.01,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,mostly being used by research institutions and government agencies.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.01,0:08:55.47,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Along the way, it helped define how file sharing works
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.47,0:08:58.55,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,and was even used to send and receive the first email.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.55,0:09:00.24,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,The network was pretty small initially,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:00.24,0:09:03.68,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,but as it grew, it quickly became a playground for hackers
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.68,0:09:06.94,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,eager to push the boundaries of technology and communication.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:07.36,0:09:09.31,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,ARPANET also just happened to be
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.31,0:09:11.54,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,the first computer network to get infected.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.18,0:09:19.13,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,In 1971, a computer scientist by the name of Bob Thomas created what is widely accepted as the first computer virus,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.13,0:09:21.04,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,now known as the Creeper virus.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.04,0:09:25.16,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,This computer worm replicated itself and spread to other systems using ARPANET.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:25.16,0:09:28.57,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,It was developed by Bob while working at a technology research firm,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.57,0:09:30.25,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,and unlike most viruses,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.25,0:09:32.63,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,it wasn't made with any malicious intent.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.63,0:09:34.98,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,The virus didn't cause any damage to your system,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.98,0:09:36.81,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,but instead displayed a message:
Comment: 0,0:09:37.39,0:09:38.14,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"I'm the creeper."
Comment: 0,0:09:38.76,0:09:40.03,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,"Catch Me If You Can."
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.00,0:09:42.24,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,It's actually kind of funny.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:42.24,0:09:44.56,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Because this playful yet disruptive act
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.56,0:09:49.61,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,foreshadowed the cat and mouse game between hackers and security professionals that continues to this day.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.73,0:09:56.88,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,The 1970s marked a turning point, as hackers began to forge their own identity and beliefs.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.88,0:10:00.65,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Rumblings of what would become known as the free software movement began to circulate.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.65,0:10:03.29,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Essential books that shaped hacker culture were published.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:03.29,0:10:06.81,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,The decade even saw the emergence of something called the Jargon File,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.81,0:10:11.04,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,which acted as a dictionary of slang used by hackers and computer programmers.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.04,0:10:15.64,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,It was things like this that further solidified the community's shared language and values.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.64,0:10:18.92,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,However, the one thing the culture lacked during this moment in time
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.92,0:10:20.52,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,was a central meeting ground.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.52,0:10:22.05,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Sure, ARPANET existed.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.05,0:10:26.56,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,But again, it was usually restricted to institutions funded by the US government.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.56,0:10:30.69,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,Local meet-ups like The Homebrew Computer Club offered some networking opportunities,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.85,0:10:34.54,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,but their accessibility was limited only to those who could physically attend.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.13,0:10:39.03,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,The good news was, it wouldn't take too long to fill this cultural void.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:39.03,0:10:40.27,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,In 1978,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.27,0:10:44.39,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,two guys from Chicago developed something called computer bulletin board systems,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.39,0:10:47.35,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,serving as the first virtual meeting place for early hackers.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:47.35,0:10:49.93,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,BBS allowed users to dial in with their modems,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.93,0:10:53.58,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,exchange messages, share software, and participate in discussions,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.58,0:10:57.70,原文 Gantari,原文,0,0,0,,laying the groundwork for the incoming rise of the hacker groups.
